## The short answer

Own the pattern plainly, describe the change you are making, and ask about the impact without demanding reassurance. Put the next meetings in a protected slot with a defined reschedule rule. Trust returns through kept commitments, not a long apology.

## When this guidance fits

Use this when you have repeatedly canceled, shortened, or moved the meeting at the last minute. If the cadence is structurally impossible, choose a schedule you can actually keep rather than promising a perfect frequency.

> **Stop and get support:** route serious concerns raised during the repair through the proper HR, safety, or reporting channel. A trust repair conversation does not change your formal responsibilities.

## 1 — See

Count the actual cancellations and late moves. Do not soften the record with “things have been busy.” Notice which meetings you protected instead. Identify the scheduling condition you can change: time of day, buffer, delegate coverage, or a same-week reschedule rule.

## 2 — Choose

Use a brief repair followed by a behavioral system change. Ask how the cancellations affected the person’s ability to raise issues. Do not make the direct report accept your apology or prove that no harm occurred.

## 3 — Say

> “I canceled or moved three of our last five one-on-ones with little notice. That broke a commitment and made this time unreliable. I’m sorry. I have moved us out of the incident window and set a rule that if I must cancel, I offer a same-week replacement before removing the meeting. What impact has the pattern had for you?”

Listen without explaining the calendar. End with: “The next four dates are protected. I’ll let the kept pattern show the change.”

## If they respond with…

### “It’s fine.”

Do not press them to disclose frustration. “Thank you. I still want to correct the pattern, and you can tell me later if there is an impact I should understand.”

### “I stopped saving topics because we never meet.”

Accept the consequence. Ask how they prefer to capture topics and follow through on the next scheduled time.

### “Emergencies happen.”

Agree without using that as absolution. “They do. My job is to build a recovery rule so emergencies do not silently erase this commitment.”

## 4 — Sustain

Keep four meetings before asking whether trust is repaired. If you must move one, use the stated rule. Do not create false certainty; a stable biweekly meeting is more trustworthy than a weekly promise you routinely break.

